        <subsection xml:id="subsec-Rlating-exterior-angles-and-the-numer-of-sides-of-a-polygon">
            <title>Relating exterior angles and the numer of sides of a polygon</title>
            <p>
                <term>Exterior angles</term> are the angles between a polygon and the extended line from the next side.
            </p>
            <p>
                Given the parallelogram below, the exterior angles are;

            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle p, \angle l, \angle s \text{ and } \angle u</m>
            </p>
            
             <figure>
                <caption>Angles in a straight line</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Exterior-angles" platform="geogebra" width="90%" aspect="4:3">
                <slate xml:id="geogebra-exterior-angles" surface="geogebra" material="kychybqc" aspect="4:3">
                enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>

            <p>
                Sum of exterior angles of a polygon is always equal to <m>360^\circ.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Exterior angle + its corresponding interior angle <m>=180^\circ.</m> i.e.
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>p + q = 180^\circ</me>
                <me>r + l = 180^\circ</me>
                <me>u + w = 180^\circ</me>
                <me>s + t = 180^\circ</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Learning point</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                To get the size of exterior angle of a regular polygon, divide <m>360^\circ</m> by the number of sides of the polygon.
            </p>
             <p>
                Size of exterior angle <m> = \frac{360^\circ}{n}</m>.
            </p>

   
        </subsection>